{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bca48275-82bb-473c-b99c-23e4922b85a8","content":"Here's the evaluation performance analysis for `EvalHeavy.csproj`:\n\n## Issues Found\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (High Impact)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nReading files during evaluation blocks the MSBuild engine. This runs on **every evaluation** (design-time builds, restores, etc.). Move file reading to a target with `Inputs/Outputs` so it only runs at execution time.\n\n### 2. Broad Glob Pattern (Medium Impact)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` walks the entire directory tree during evaluation. If the tree contains large folders (e.g., `node_modules`, `.git`, artifacts), this becomes expensive. Narrow the glob or add exclusions via `DefaultItemExcludes`.\n\n### 3. Chained Import Depth (Low Impact)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nThree levels deep is modest, but this pattern can grow. Deep import chains increase evaluation time linearly. Keep chains shallow and avoid unnecessary layering.\n\n---\n\n**Recommended fixes:** Replace the `File::ReadAllText` call with a target-based approach, and restrict the glob to specific file extensions you actually need.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5b551b20-6f58-4f5f-bfcb-66df2ef62d4e","outputTokens":343,"requestId":"1C33:1376AB:C47EC3:E52270:69F400E4"},"id":"2e148f0e-5bac-478e-9fba-e619adf8d173","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:25:02.423Z","parentId":"a543875d-6d0d-4114-9825-1b3ce75113aa"}
